That was totally unexpected.

231
00:07:24,921 --> 00:07:26,490
- The transfer form.
- That was unbelievable.

232
00:07:26,491 --> 00:07:28,860
Names, Choo Shin Soo, Shin Gi Ru, Hong Yun Hwa, and Shin Hyun Soo.

233
00:07:28,861 --> 00:07:31,191
- Welcome!
- It's nice to meet you all!

234
00:07:32,031 --> 00:07:34,800
The first item is "Special Note."

235
00:07:34,801 --> 00:07:37,370
Shin Soo wrote, "Retirement from baseball."

236
00:07:37,371 --> 00:07:39,170
- You officially retired recently.
- That's right.

237
00:07:39,171 --> 00:07:40,171
Yes, I did.

238
00:07:40,901 --> 00:07:44,441
("Choo Shin Soo, 1st Asian Player in MLB to Hit 200 Home Runs")

239
00:07:44,911 --> 00:07:48,441
("Choo Shin Soo, 1st Korean Hitter in MLB to Win Player of the Month")

240
00:07:49,151 --> 00:07:51,380
(The legend continues in Korea.)

241
00:07:51,381 --> 00:07:53,380
It's flying to the left side. It's flying high and far.

242
00:07:53,381 --> 00:07:56,290
He ended the game with a home run!

243
00:07:56,291 --> 00:07:59,661
("Choo Shin Soo, Oldest Player in KBO to Achieve 20-20 Club")

244
00:08:00,221 --> 00:08:05,231
(Setting numerous records,)

245
00:08:05,901 --> 00:08:09,501
(he's driven forward in the past 34 years.)

246
00:08:10,471 --> 00:08:14,241
(It's time for him to end the journey.)

247
00:08:15,241 --> 00:08:19,341
(Many fans came to see his retirement ceremony.)

248
00:08:19,781 --> 00:08:23,881
I could never imagine this day would come to me.

249
00:08:24,651 --> 00:08:27,120
I thought I'd keep playing baseball, which I love,

250
00:08:27,121 --> 00:08:28,721
for the rest of my life.

251
00:08:29,491 --> 00:08:32,160
I didn't make it this far on my own.

252
00:08:32,161 --> 00:08:36,460
There have been many unbelievably great people around me.

253
00:08:36,461 --> 00:08:37,830
I'd like to thank them wholeheartedly.

254
00:08:37,831 --> 00:08:42,601
(I'd like to thank them wholeheartedly.)

255
00:08:45,801 --> 00:08:46,940
How do you feel about it?

256
00:08:46,941 --> 00:08:50,010
Was there any specific reason behind your decision to retire?

257
00:08:50,011 --> 00:08:53,180
As for me, I announced my retirement beforehand.

258
00:08:53,181 --> 00:08:56,450
- Oh, right.
- After the 2023 season ended...

259
00:08:56,451 --> 00:08:58,480
When the 2024 season began,

260
00:08:58,481 --> 00:09:02,021
I announced that I would retire after the season.

261
00:09:02,451 --> 00:09:04,320
And here's why I decided to retire.

262
00:09:04,321 --> 00:09:07,260
During the spring training camp in 2024, I injured my shoulder.

263
00:09:07,261 --> 00:09:08,261
- Oh, no.
- I see.

264
00:09:08,791 --> 00:09:10,860
I thought it was a minor injury,

265
00:09:10,861 --> 00:09:13,660
but the pain became severe as time passed...

266
00:09:13,661 --> 00:09:15,301
to the point that I couldn't even practice.

267
00:09:15,931 --> 00:09:19,401
Ho Dong and Jang Hoon must know this as they used to be athletes.

268
00:09:19,671 --> 00:09:23,310
There should be a good process for us to achieve a good result.

269
00:09:23,311 --> 00:09:26,180
But since my shoulder hurt, I couldn't train myself.

270
00:09:26,181 --> 00:09:27,681
- Right.
- So...

271
00:09:28,081 --> 00:09:30,050
I couldn't go through any process...

272
00:09:30,051 --> 00:09:32,881
that would help me accept either a good or bad result.

273
00:09:33,381 --> 00:09:36,651
So when I was in the dugout watching my junior players playing,

274
00:09:36,951 --> 00:09:40,290
seeing myself watching the game in the dugout...

275
00:09:40,291 --> 00:09:41,991
was very satisfactory.

276
00:09:42,631 --> 00:09:45,091
Before that, I thought I was supposed to be on the field.

277
00:09:46,261 --> 00:09:48,701
But I was feeling comfortable being in the dugout,

278
00:09:49,631 --> 00:09:51,870
which made me realize it was over for me.

279
00:09:51,871 --> 00:09:55,000
I realized that I no longer had passion...

280
00:09:55,001 --> 00:09:56,671
for baseball.

281
00:09:57,211 --> 00:09:59,781
Since it was my last season before the retirement,

282
00:10:00,011 --> 00:10:02,581
the coach tried to help me bring it to a successful end.

283
00:10:02,711 --> 00:10:04,681
So he included me in the lineup for every game.

284
00:10:05,651 --> 00:10:08,551
So the next day, I went to see the coach.

285
00:10:09,451 --> 00:10:13,690
I said, "Coach, I've never played baseball like this before."

286
00:10:13,691 --> 00:10:18,260
"In the past 34 years, I've gone through a long process..."

287
00:10:18,261 --> 00:10:20,100
"to achieve a good result."

288
00:10:20,101 --> 00:10:21,731
"But since I wasn't able to go through such a process,"

289
00:10:22,531 --> 00:10:24,871
"when I see myself playing on the field,"

290
00:10:25,231 --> 00:10:28,141
"it doesn't feel right."

291
00:10:28,911 --> 00:10:31,240
"It feels like I'm damaging my baseball career..."

292
00:10:31,241 --> 00:10:32,981
"that I've built in the past 34 years."

293
00:10:33,381 --> 00:10:36,310
"I don't want to feel ashamed of myself anymore."

294
00:10:36,311 --> 00:10:40,320
I asked him to give more chances to the ones who made more efforts...

295
00:10:40,321 --> 00:10:42,290
and not to include me in the lineup...

296
00:10:42,291 --> 00:10:44,291
for the remaining games of the season.

297
00:10:44,821 --> 00:10:48,121
What I said to the coach broke his heart.

298
00:10:48,261 --> 00:10:52,031
After that, I stayed in the dugout to the end of the season.

299
00:10:52,201 --> 00:10:53,831
- That's right.
- I still had pain in my shoulder.

300
00:10:53,931 --> 00:10:55,901
In the final game of the season,

301
00:10:56,471 --> 00:10:58,871
I played as a substitute, which is how I ended the season.

302
00:10:59,401 --> 00:11:02,411
(The last game before his retirement)

303
00:11:02,741 --> 00:11:06,281
(Choo Shin Soo is getting into the batter's box.)

304
00:11:08,951 --> 00:11:13,621
(Choo Choo Train runs on the field for the last time.)

305
00:11:14,721 --> 00:11:19,961
(His fellow athletes came to see him off at the end of his journey.)

306
00:11:20,861 --> 00:11:26,161
(He ended his 34-year journey as a baseball player.)

307
00:11:26,331 --> 00:11:30,201
At your retirement ceremony, you burst into tears, right?

308
00:11:30,431 --> 00:11:32,470
- I'm sure he did.
- I really didn't want to cry...

309
00:11:32,471 --> 00:11:34,871
- because I was very happy.
- I see.

310
00:11:35,171 --> 00:11:39,141
- I loved that one thing in my life.
- That's right.

311
00:11:39,541 --> 00:11:41,640
And I was loved by many fans.

312
00:11:41,641 --> 00:11:43,181
I had no reason to cry.

313
00:11:43,311 --> 00:11:45,451
So I told myself not to cry before the ceremony.

314
00:11:45,751 --> 00:11:47,421
- During my retirement speech...
- I also know it well.

315
00:11:48,021 --> 00:11:50,050
While speaking, I was telling myself in my head,

316
00:11:50,051 --> 00:11:51,691
"I'm giving a lecture, not a retirement speech."

317
00:11:51,751 --> 00:11:54,760
- I focused on negative thoughts.
- People do that to avoid crying.

318
00:11:54,761 --> 00:11:56,760
- That's right.
- I tried biting my tongue too.

319
00:11:56,761 --> 00:11:58,261
But at the end,

320
00:11:59,031 --> 00:12:00,731
I mentioned my family.

321
00:12:01,001 --> 00:12:02,530
- Of course.
- I couldn't hold back tears then.

322
00:12:02,531 --> 00:12:04,101
You can't hold back tears when you get emotional.

323
00:12:05,071 --> 00:12:06,941
Now I'm going to...

324
00:12:09,541 --> 00:12:14,441
(I'm going to talk about my family.)

325
00:12:16,951 --> 00:12:20,881
(He couldn't get the words out.)

326
00:12:21,651 --> 00:12:23,550
(My goal was not to cry here.)

327
00:12:23,551 --> 00:12:26,690
(But it's not easy.)

328
00:12:26,691 --> 00:12:29,790
- But you played for a long time.
- True.

329
00:12:29,791 --> 00:12:31,860
- How old are you now? Forty...
- I'm forty-three.

330
00:12:31,861 --> 00:12:32,960
Right. He played for a long time.

331
00:12:32,961 --> 00:12:35,160
Ho Dong retired earlier than most ssireum players.

332
00:12:35,161 --> 00:12:37,731
- Ho Dong...
- I haven't retired from ssireum.

333
00:12:38,201 --> 00:12:40,201
- You haven't retired yet?
- Are you an active ssireum player?

334
00:12:40,541 --> 00:12:43,511
- I could make my comeback anytime.
- Oh, I didn't know that.

335
00:12:43,741 --> 00:12:45,940
- Why haven't you until now?
- I would slam my opponent down.

336
00:12:45,941 --> 00:12:47,410
I still can do it.

337
00:12:47,411 --> 00:12:48,641
It's an open ending.

338
00:12:48,881 --> 00:12:50,951
I haven't retired yet.

339
00:12:51,611 --> 00:12:55,120
Your team won in 2022, apparently.

340
00:12:55,121 --> 00:12:56,220
It was the first time your team had won?

341
00:12:56,221 --> 00:12:57,351
- Yes.
- Since his debut?

342
00:12:57,621 --> 00:12:59,920
(The 2022 Korean series)

343
00:12:59,921 --> 00:13:02,021
(Winner of the 2022 Korean series)

344
00:13:02,961 --> 00:13:05,131
When I was an amateur player, my teams won many times.

345
00:13:05,231 --> 00:13:06,700
But my teams didn't win...

346
00:13:06,701 --> 00:13:08,201
- after I became a pro.
- You weren't professional.

347
00:13:08,261 --> 00:13:09,270
Right.

348
00:13:09,271 --> 00:13:11,500
- I mean... Why? Why is that?
- That's funny.

349
00:13:11,501 --> 00:13:13,200
- Shin Soo, Hee Chul is right.
- Yes, he's right.

350
00:13:13,201 --> 00:13:14,770
He's talking nonsense because he knows nothing about baseball.

351
00:13:14,771 --> 00:13:17,511
- This is how famous he is.
- If it was the first time...

352
00:13:17,671 --> 00:13:18,870
I know nothing about sports,

353
00:13:18,871 --> 00:13:20,080
- but I know Shin Soo.
- You mean, Men on a Mission?

354
00:13:20,081 --> 00:13:22,880
You must've had mixed feelings when your team won. How did it feel?

355
00:13:22,881 --> 00:13:24,880
- Since I became a professional...
- He must've cried.

356
00:13:24,881 --> 00:13:26,821
I realized that it was what made me start playing baseball.

357
00:13:26,921 --> 00:13:28,480
- Right.
- The thought came to me right away.

358
00:13:28,481 --> 00:13:31,850
- I was a pro for over 20 years.
- That's hard to believe.

359
00:13:31,851 --> 00:13:34,090
I felt like I was rewarded for my hard work for all those years.

360
00:13:34,091 --> 00:13:35,120
(He felt like his efforts in his 34-year career had paid off.)

361
00:13:35,121 --> 00:13:37,360
Let's say you did a tremendous job that year.

362
00:13:37,361 --> 00:13:39,930
You hit 100 home runs.

363
00:13:39,931 --> 00:13:41,361
You were on base 500 times.

364
00:13:41,901 --> 00:13:43,601
You also stole bases 50 times.

365
00:13:43,971 --> 00:13:45,101
Would you still be happier about the team's victory?

366
00:13:46,101 --> 00:13:48,771
I must say, 200 home runs are a lot.

367
00:13:49,271 --> 00:13:50,940
That kind of record would remain in baseball history.

368
00:13:50,941 --> 00:13:52,841
- But...
- Right. It's a rare record.

369
00:13:53,011 --> 00:13:55,311
I'm not sure, but I think I'd be happier about my team's victory.

370
00:13:55,851 --> 00:13:57,580
- Because baseball is a team sport.
- Here's why.

371
00:13:57,581 --> 00:14:00,781
I'd stand out if I set such records,

372
00:14:00,981 --> 00:14:03,190
- but my team wouldn't.
- That's a great thing to say.

373
00:14:03,191 --> 00:14:04,720
Then Shin Soo, do you think there's a player...

374
00:14:04,721 --> 00:14:06,261
- who's greater than a team?
- Oh, right.

375
00:14:07,021 --> 00:14:09,131
To be honest, I don't think there is.

376
00:14:09,561 --> 00:14:10,730
To be honest, I don't think there is.

377
00:14:10,731 --> 00:14:13,061
- What? But we have one here.
- There is.

378
00:14:13,461 --> 00:14:15,831
Right. I watched the episode.

379
00:14:17,271 --> 00:14:19,300
(Here is the player who's greater than a team.)

380
00:14:19,301 --> 00:14:20,471
He's the player who's greater than a team.

381
00:14:21,401 --> 00:14:22,770
(There's no player who's greater than a team.)

382
00:14:22,771 --> 00:14:24,041
(There is. Me!)

383
00:14:25,011 --> 00:14:26,941
(There is. Me!)

384
00:14:27,211 --> 00:14:28,341
Let's have a debate on this topic.

385
00:14:28,481 --> 00:14:30,151
You think there's no player greater than a team?

386
00:14:30,981 --> 00:14:32,181
In my opinion...

387
00:14:32,451 --> 00:14:34,750
Let's say I hit a home run. When a player hits a home run,

388
00:14:34,751 --> 00:14:37,220
- no one else but him stands out.
- Right.

389
00:14:37,221 --> 00:14:39,291
But from my perspective on baseball,

390
00:14:39,421 --> 00:14:41,320
a player is able to hit a home run...

391
00:14:41,321 --> 00:14:43,490
because the players before and after him do well.

392
00:14:43,491 --> 00:14:45,461
- I agree.
- That's a great remark.

393
00:14:45,801 --> 00:14:48,031
Right. Someone I know whose family name is Seo...

394
00:14:48,601 --> 00:14:50,671
doesn't think an assist matters at all.

395
00:14:51,371 --> 00:14:52,400
- He thinks...
- But...

396
00:14:52,401 --> 00:14:55,301
As if he produced balls like in bowling and shot three-pointers,

397
00:14:55,811 --> 00:14:58,271
- two-pointers, and layups.
- Produce balls?

398
00:14:58,871 --> 00:15:00,141
- As if he could create balls.
- Then...

399
00:15:00,581 --> 00:15:02,950
What do you think? He said there was no player who's greater than a team.

400
00:15:02,951 --> 00:15:05,850
In normal situations,

401
00:15:05,851 --> 00:15:07,550
especially in cases of ball sports,

402
00:15:07,551 --> 00:15:10,151
they're team sports, so Shin Soo is right about it.

403
00:15:10,651 --> 00:15:12,790
When your team wins a season,

404
00:15:12,791 --> 00:15:14,791
- it's a great honor.
- That's right.

405
00:15:15,091 --> 00:15:18,361
But once is a lifetime, among many athletes,

406
00:15:19,101 --> 00:15:21,631
exceptionally superb ones appear.

407
00:15:22,801 --> 00:15:24,970
- He's referring to himself.
- "Exceptionally superb."

408
00:15:24,971 --> 00:15:27,301
- Exceptionally...
- "Exceptionally."

409
00:15:28,241 --> 00:15:32,341
Normally, a team is greater than a player.

410
00:15:32,441 --> 00:15:33,641
- That's right.
- But...

411
00:15:34,041 --> 00:15:35,181
- there are...
- My gosh.

412
00:15:36,581 --> 00:15:38,181
some athletes who appear...

413
00:15:38,611 --> 00:15:40,020
- once in a very long time, - An exceptional athlete.

414
00:15:40,021 --> 00:15:42,551
which happens very rarely.

415
00:15:42,791 --> 00:15:44,990
So in rare cases, there's a player...

416
00:15:44,991 --> 00:15:47,160
- who's greater than a team.
- There is such a player?

417
00:15:47,161 --> 00:15:48,490
- My goodness.
- That's what I'm trying to say.

418
00:15:48,491 --> 00:15:50,230
- Try to understand him.
- He's one in a millennium.

419
00:15:50,231 --> 00:15:52,161
- He's extremely rare.
- Exactly.

420
00:15:52,431 --> 00:15:53,601
- Right.
- Shin Soo, do you understand that?

421
00:15:53,631 --> 00:15:54,660
- He thinks he's special.
- Right.

422
00:15:54,661 --> 00:15:57,031
It's true that he has exceptional talent.

423
00:15:57,131 --> 00:15:58,801
- We just have different opinions.
- Then...

424
00:15:58,901 --> 00:16:01,201
There's a very famous major leaguer.

425
00:16:01,471 --> 00:16:04,011
Like Kim Byung Hyun whom we all love so much.

426
00:16:04,341 --> 00:16:08,241
- Mr. Middle Finger.
- Byung Hyun has...

427
00:16:08,441 --> 00:16:10,810
- two World Series rings.
- He has World Series rings.

428
00:16:10,811 --> 00:16:11,850
Right. He has those rings.

429
00:16:11,851 --> 00:16:13,021
He was the 1st Asian player to win 2 of such rings.

430
00:16:13,121 --> 00:16:16,090
I'm so jealous of the players...

431
00:16:16,091 --> 00:16:17,691
- who have World Series rings.
- Really?

432
00:16:17,791 --> 00:16:20,820
- It's a shame...
- I once even said this jokingly.

433
00:16:20,821 --> 00:16:23,291
- What is it?
- I was asked...

434
00:16:23,861 --> 00:16:27,901
if I would trade the seven years of my salary...

435
00:16:28,831 --> 00:16:32,771
that I received from Texas Rangers for one World Series ring.

436
00:16:33,271 --> 00:16:35,500
I didn't think for a second and said I would definitely do so.

437
00:16:35,501 --> 00:16:36,671
For one of those rings?

438
00:16:37,041 --> 00:16:40,410
- A World Series ring is historic.
- It's an honor.

439
00:16:40,411 --> 00:16:43,381
The fact that you won the series in that particular year...

440
00:16:43,551 --> 00:16:46,621
remains forever no matter how much time passes...

441
00:16:46,721 --> 00:16:47,920
- unless this country disappears.
- Right.

442
00:16:47,921 --> 00:16:50,421
Byung Hyun just leaves those rings lying around.

443
00:16:51,451 --> 00:16:53,860
When he makes burgers, he put them on the grill.

444
00:16:53,861 --> 00:16:54,920
- Really?
- When he's...

445
00:16:54,921 --> 00:16:58,030
- working at his burger place, - That's not true.

446
00:16:58,031 --> 00:16:59,700
- those rings are just lying around.
- Such valuable rings...

447
00:16:59,701 --> 00:17:00,730
("Kim Byung Hyun Loses World Series Rings and Finds Them in Trunk")

448
00:17:00,731 --> 00:17:02,031
Byung Hyun wouldn't do that.

449
00:17:02,201 --> 00:17:05,941
- Shin Soo, you've retired.
- Yes.

450
00:17:06,171 --> 00:17:08,940
Then... This might sound funny, but how will you make ends meet?

451
00:17:08,941 --> 00:17:10,140
("Choo Shin Soo's Total Salary Received Is 190 Million Dollars")

452
00:17:10,141 --> 00:17:12,340
- You need to earn money.
- What will you do to make a living?

453
00:17:12,341 --> 00:17:14,911
You see, Byung Hyun runs a burger place.

454
00:17:15,041 --> 00:17:17,381
There are 30 teams in the Major League.

455
00:17:17,511 --> 00:17:20,421
As a player, I've been to all 30 stadiums.

456
00:17:20,951 --> 00:17:24,920
But I want to visit the 30 stadiums as a baseball fan.

457
00:17:24,921 --> 00:17:26,090
- That would be fun.
- That's so cool.

458
00:17:26,091 --> 00:17:27,520
I calculated the time.

459
00:17:27,521 --> 00:17:29,930
- It'll take about three months.
- That's a long time.

460
00:17:29,931 --> 00:17:33,361
At each stadium, they sell different kinds of food.

461
00:17:33,661 --> 00:17:35,100
So I want to try all that delicious food...

462
00:17:35,101 --> 00:17:36,270
- Will you join me?
- Yes... Oh, my.

463
00:17:36,271 --> 00:17:37,271
- Will you join me?
- Yes... Oh, my.

464
00:17:37,271 --> 00:17:38,271
Why are you flirting with me?

465
00:17:39,271 --> 00:17:40,540
- "Flirting?"
- She's taken, Shin Soo.

466
00:17:40,541 --> 00:17:41,671
She thought he was flirting with her.

467
00:17:41,771 --> 00:17:45,540
- Gi Ru, I'm begging you...
- Why would he flirt with me?

468
00:17:45,541 --> 00:17:47,440
- What? Why?
- Change your pattern of thinking.

469
00:17:47,441 --> 00:17:49,850
- Why?
- Whenever a man is kind to you,

470
00:17:49,851 --> 00:17:50,881
you think he's flirting with you.

