963
00:34:16,301 --> 00:34:19,670
I was definitely going to go for the third base.

964
00:34:19,671 --> 00:34:21,040
Right.

965
00:34:21,041 --> 00:34:22,270
The moment I hit it,

966
00:34:22,271 --> 00:34:24,010
I put in my full energy.

967
00:34:24,011 --> 00:34:27,710
I ran at the fastest speed I could.

968
00:34:27,711 --> 00:34:30,281
Luckily, the ball hit the fence...

969
00:34:30,711 --> 00:34:31,810
and went past the fielder.

970
00:34:31,811 --> 00:34:33,651
(He made a great slide into 3rd base.)

971
00:34:33,921 --> 00:34:36,620
- Seriously. It just worked out.
- A double is fine.

972
00:34:36,621 --> 00:34:38,390
Let's say he hit a home run, a triple,

973
00:34:38,391 --> 00:34:40,460
a double, and he is left with a single.

974
00:34:40,461 --> 00:34:43,260
But it went through the left-center.

975
00:34:43,261 --> 00:34:44,730
- He would have to run slowly.
- What about the score?

976
00:34:44,731 --> 00:34:46,730
- Right.
- They're losing by one score.

977
00:34:46,731 --> 00:34:49,701
When he comes to the first base,

978
00:34:50,401 --> 00:34:51,870
it would make him think.

979
00:34:51,871 --> 00:34:54,100
If the score difference is large,

980
00:34:54,101 --> 00:34:56,370
I may not go.

981
00:34:56,371 --> 00:34:59,510
But if it's doable, like 4, 5, or 6 points,

982
00:34:59,511 --> 00:35:01,040
I think it's right...

983
00:35:01,041 --> 00:35:04,050
to focus on the game rather than my records.

984
00:35:04,051 --> 00:35:05,180
Team before me.

985
00:35:05,181 --> 00:35:06,310
Even when the score difference is 4 or 5?

986
00:35:06,311 --> 00:35:07,950
Of course. I would go.

987
00:35:07,951 --> 00:35:10,850
Shin Soo became the first Korean hitter...

988
00:35:10,851 --> 00:35:13,220
to appear in the MLB All-Star Game...

989
00:35:13,221 --> 00:35:15,090
in 2018.

990
00:35:15,091 --> 00:35:16,460
- All-Star Game?
- All-Star Game?

991
00:35:16,461 --> 00:35:17,830
That's really amazing.

992
00:35:17,831 --> 00:35:19,430
Do you get benefits?

993
00:35:19,431 --> 00:35:21,630
- All-Star benefits.
- I'm curious about this.

994
00:35:21,631 --> 00:35:24,370
There is a reason why everyone aims to go to the Major League.

995
00:35:24,371 --> 00:35:26,300
It gathers the best players...

996
00:35:26,301 --> 00:35:28,041
- all around the world.
- Right.

997
00:35:28,471 --> 00:35:30,970
Benefits aside, the players are provided...

998
00:35:30,971 --> 00:35:32,741
the environment in which they can focus on playing baseball.

999
00:35:33,541 --> 00:35:34,741
There are so many people...

1000
00:35:35,041 --> 00:35:37,081
who help you with things other than baseball.

1001
00:35:37,881 --> 00:35:39,750
There's a team that helps your family...

1002
00:35:39,751 --> 00:35:41,520
when they have trouble.

1003
00:35:41,521 --> 00:35:42,820
- Really?
- There's a team for that?

1004
00:35:42,821 --> 00:35:44,121
Really?

1005
00:35:44,491 --> 00:35:47,490
- You can focus on baseball only.
- You can just do your job.

1006
00:35:47,491 --> 00:35:48,491
What if it's your wedding anniversary...

1007
00:35:48,491 --> 00:35:49,491
but you're too busy to go?

1008
00:35:49,492 --> 00:35:51,360
- They congratulate her for him.
- They do it for him.

1009
00:35:51,361 --> 00:35:53,860
If the players make a request,

1010
00:35:53,861 --> 00:35:55,400
they send flowers.

1011
00:35:55,401 --> 00:35:56,900
Really?

1012
00:35:56,901 --> 00:35:58,400
Is there something like a counseling camp for couples...

1013
00:35:58,401 --> 00:35:59,871
when things don't go well between them?

1014
00:36:00,371 --> 00:36:02,040
"Baseball Camp."

1015
00:36:02,041 --> 00:36:03,770
- In that way...
- Jang Hoon will go there.

1016
00:36:03,771 --> 00:36:05,170
They could convince your wife...

1017
00:36:05,171 --> 00:36:06,740
- so you can focus on the games.
- Min Chul and Jang Hoon...

1018
00:36:06,741 --> 00:36:08,040
They'll be ready.

1019
00:36:08,041 --> 00:36:09,910
will surround you.

1020
00:36:09,911 --> 00:36:11,580
- I think it would exist.
- "Baseball Camp."

1021
00:36:11,581 --> 00:36:12,910
- Like psychological counseling.
- I think it would exist.

1022
00:36:12,911 --> 00:36:14,350
There are counselors.

1023
00:36:14,351 --> 00:36:15,550
Right.

1024
00:36:15,551 --> 00:36:17,520
- Police officers are there...
- For mental care.

1025
00:36:17,521 --> 00:36:19,850
to always keep the players safe.

1026
00:36:19,851 --> 00:36:21,520
- They follow you?
- That's interesting.

1027
00:36:21,521 --> 00:36:23,420
- They have a good system.
- They have a good system.

1028
00:36:23,421 --> 00:36:25,790
It would have felt weird when you left the Major League.

1029
00:36:25,791 --> 00:36:27,600
- Right.
- Also when you retire.

1030
00:36:27,601 --> 00:36:32,100
Actually, when you enter the locker room,

1031
00:36:32,101 --> 00:36:33,871
you see the back of the uniforms...

1032
00:36:34,101 --> 00:36:36,800
with the names and the numbers.

1033
00:36:36,801 --> 00:36:38,470
- Right.
- They're all there.

1034
00:36:38,471 --> 00:36:40,540
- Right.
- Whenever I looked...

1035
00:36:40,541 --> 00:36:43,011
at my uniform,

1036
00:36:43,511 --> 00:36:45,811
I felt like a special person.

1037
00:36:46,311 --> 00:36:49,520
I was an Asian player in such a great place,

1038
00:36:49,521 --> 00:36:52,590
and I wasn't tall...

1039
00:36:52,591 --> 00:36:55,490
or big in build like others.

1040
00:36:55,491 --> 00:36:58,791
But walking to my locker...

1041
00:36:59,091 --> 00:37:02,160
while looking at my uniform with my name...

1042
00:37:02,161 --> 00:37:04,671
in the Major League...

1043
00:37:05,201 --> 00:37:06,971
really felt like I was floating in the sky.

1044
00:37:07,671 --> 00:37:11,671
The day of the last match of the last year of my contract.

1045
00:37:12,511 --> 00:37:14,140
I looked at my uniform that day.

1046
00:37:14,141 --> 00:37:16,440
I was the first to enter the locker room that day.

1047
00:37:16,441 --> 00:37:17,980
I walked that short distance...

1048
00:37:17,981 --> 00:37:19,980
of about 30m.

1049
00:37:19,981 --> 00:37:21,921
I looked at it and tears came down.

1050
00:37:24,291 --> 00:37:25,950
I felt,

1051
00:37:25,951 --> 00:37:30,220
"This might be my last day wearing the Major League uniform."

1052
00:37:30,221 --> 00:37:31,931
That came to my mind.

1053
00:37:33,831 --> 00:37:38,471
(He dedicated his youth to his dream stage, MLB.)

1054
00:37:38,901 --> 00:37:43,041
(The shining days of his life that will forever shine)

1055
00:37:43,141 --> 00:37:45,210
The Texas team didn't forget you, though.

1056
00:37:45,211 --> 00:37:47,380
I heard you received an award recently.

1057
00:37:47,381 --> 00:37:49,011
- Texas.
- Texas.

1058
00:37:49,311 --> 00:37:50,480
I was living in Korea,

1059
00:37:50,481 --> 00:37:52,810
and they contacted me from Texas.

1060
00:37:52,811 --> 00:37:54,851
They wanted to give me an award on that date,

1061
00:37:55,181 --> 00:37:57,021
- so they asked if I was available.
- That's so amazing.

1062
00:37:57,151 --> 00:37:59,390
I should clear my schedule for that.

1063
00:37:59,391 --> 00:38:01,060
That's right.

1064
00:38:01,061 --> 00:38:02,090
They were going to give you an award.

1065
00:38:02,091 --> 00:38:04,090
- "When is the date?"
- So...

1066
00:38:04,091 --> 00:38:07,930
A person's true worth is revealed...

1067
00:38:07,931 --> 00:38:09,560
- When they're absent.
- not when they are present,

1068
00:38:09,561 --> 00:38:11,330
- but when they are absent.
- Those are great words.

1069
00:38:11,331 --> 00:38:13,131
- That's so cool.
- So...

1070
00:38:13,371 --> 00:38:16,270
It had been five years since I left the team,

1071
00:38:16,271 --> 00:38:18,510
- but they remembered me, - Right.

1072
00:38:18,511 --> 00:38:21,110
called me, and gave me an award.

1073
00:38:21,111 --> 00:38:24,210
It was the Mark Holtz Award, an achievement award.

1074
00:38:24,211 --> 00:38:26,650
It is given to players who devoted themselves to the team.

1075
00:38:26,651 --> 00:38:27,720
Those who devoted themselves.

1076
00:38:27,721 --> 00:38:29,780
- What happened to your house there?
- Right.

1077
00:38:29,781 --> 00:38:30,790
- Your house in Texas.
- Right.

1078
00:38:30,791 --> 00:38:31,990
- It's still there.
- It's still there?

1079
00:38:31,991 --> 00:38:33,150
- You still have it?
- I still have my house.

1080
00:38:33,151 --> 00:38:34,561
There...

1081
00:38:35,221 --> 00:38:36,221
Now...

1082
00:38:36,561 --> 00:38:37,561
Is that your house?

1083
00:38:38,531 --> 00:38:39,990
(A mansion has appeared.)

1084
00:38:39,991 --> 00:38:41,131
Is that a house?

1085
00:38:41,801 --> 00:38:42,961
That's a house?

1086
00:38:44,131 --> 00:38:45,170
My goodness.

1087
00:38:45,171 --> 00:38:46,401
- Hold on.
- Hi.

1088
00:38:46,501 --> 00:38:48,301
- Come in.
- What an amazing place.

1089
00:38:48,741 --> 00:38:49,841
Isn't it scorching hot?

1090
00:38:50,401 --> 00:38:53,641
(Welcome to the Choo family's house.)

1091
00:38:53,881 --> 00:38:55,780
- Gosh.
- The house. Was it 18,000m²?

1092
00:38:55,781 --> 00:38:57,250
- That's a house?
- Yes.

1093
00:38:57,251 --> 00:38:58,251
(The sight of the house is unbelievable.)

1094
00:38:58,252 --> 00:39:00,550
(This is the formal dining room.)

1095
00:39:00,551 --> 00:39:02,280
(It's rare to see in a house.)

1096
00:39:02,281 --> 00:39:04,190
(A wine cellar in my house)

1097
00:39:04,191 --> 00:39:06,620
- A winery?
- There's a winery in the house.

1098
00:39:06,621 --> 00:39:07,721
- A winery?
- Goodness.

1099
00:39:08,461 --> 00:39:09,621
(The room is air-conditioned.)

1100
00:39:10,391 --> 00:39:11,391
(It's cool in here.)

1101
00:39:11,631 --> 00:39:13,091
(It's very cool in here right now.)

1102
00:39:13,531 --> 00:39:14,601
- The temperature is set.
- Look at the cellar.

1103
00:39:14,901 --> 00:39:16,860
(It's as big as a wine bar cellar.)

1104
00:39:16,861 --> 00:39:17,930
Oh, my.

1105
00:39:17,931 --> 00:39:19,801
(It's the center of our house.)

1106
00:39:19,901 --> 00:39:22,071
(Here are the kitchen and the living room.)

1107
00:39:22,771 --> 00:39:23,810
(New spaces keep appearing.)

1108
00:39:23,811 --> 00:39:25,171
It's like a suite room.

1109
00:39:25,371 --> 00:39:27,141
- She's his wife, right?
- Probably.

1110
00:39:27,941 --> 00:39:29,711
That's my favorite place.

1111
00:39:30,411 --> 00:39:31,610
- Is it?
- Gosh.

1112
00:39:31,611 --> 00:39:33,851
- I'm jealous of the wines.
- Do 200 people live in that house?

1113
00:39:34,321 --> 00:39:35,321
- Is it a movie theater?
- Five.

1114
00:39:35,322 --> 00:39:37,190
- "Five?"
- A movie theater in a house?

1115
00:39:37,191 --> 00:39:38,921
(A private movie theater has appeared.)

1116
00:39:39,591 --> 00:39:41,020
That's amazing, Shin Soo.

1117
00:39:41,021 --> 00:39:42,521
Your future looks bright.

1118
00:39:43,421 --> 00:39:44,790
(As for our pool)

1119
00:39:44,791 --> 00:39:46,030
- A pool? My goodness.
- Oh, gosh.

1120
00:39:46,031 --> 00:39:47,230
(A hotel-like pool in the front yard)

1121
00:39:47,231 --> 00:39:48,300
- How big is it?
- That's a pool?

1122
00:39:48,301 --> 00:39:49,331
(A hotel-like pool in the front yard)

1123
00:39:50,201 --> 00:39:51,231
This room is...

1124
00:39:51,401 --> 00:39:53,030
- What's that?
- Is that a baseball field?

1125
00:39:53,031 --> 00:39:54,301
Do you even have a practice field?

1126
00:39:54,571 --> 00:39:56,600
- There's even a basketball court.
- Isn't that a bit too much?

1127
00:39:56,601 --> 00:39:59,711
(Fully equipped with a baseball museum and a gym)

1128
00:40:00,111 --> 00:40:01,741
(Let me show you around.)

1129
00:40:02,481 --> 00:40:04,611
(A wall filled with baseball plaques)

1130
00:40:04,951 --> 00:40:06,381
(My boys'...)

1131
00:40:06,681 --> 00:40:07,750
(and my husband's)

1132
00:40:07,751 --> 00:40:09,680
(computer room, every man's dream)

1133
00:40:09,681 --> 00:40:10,821
That's a computer room?

1134
00:40:11,291 --> 00:40:12,391
It's a computer room.

1135
00:40:13,151 --> 00:40:14,161
(My husband)

1136
00:40:14,361 --> 00:40:16,321
- A Lego room?
- Lego?

1137
00:40:17,091 --> 00:40:20,960
(Filled with rare Lego sets)

1138
00:40:20,961 --> 00:40:22,031
My goodness.

1139
00:40:22,161 --> 00:40:23,161
Did you know?

1140
00:40:23,162 --> 00:40:24,600
- It's...
- That's not his only house.

1141
00:40:24,601 --> 00:40:25,630
- What?
- What?

1142
00:40:25,631 --> 00:40:27,870
- Does he have another one?
- He owns another house in the US.

1143
00:40:27,871 --> 00:40:29,371
Does that mean you own two houses?

1144
00:40:29,541 --> 00:40:30,710
Two houses in the US?

1145
00:40:30,711 --> 00:40:32,310
Then... Aren't I right?

1146
00:40:32,311 --> 00:40:34,181
He has two houses, which is everyone's dream.

1147
00:40:34,411 --> 00:40:37,281
- Where's your other house?
- While that house was being built,

1148
00:40:37,481 --> 00:40:38,851
there was already another house next door.

1149
00:40:38,981 --> 00:40:41,981
But compared to our current house,

1150
00:40:42,481 --> 00:40:43,581
- the other one is bigger.
- Bigger?

1151
00:40:44,291 --> 00:40:46,690
It's the land that's big, not the house.

1152
00:40:46,691 --> 00:40:47,720
That's cool.

1153
00:40:47,721 --> 00:40:50,290
In that house, there's a pond in the back. You can even fish.

1154
00:40:50,291 --> 00:40:51,760
- At home?
- We also have a stable.

1155
00:40:51,761 --> 00:40:52,830
A stable?

1156
00:40:52,831 --> 00:40:54,660
- While building our current house, - Even a stable?

1157
00:40:54,661 --> 00:40:56,361
our neighbor didn't seem...

1158
00:40:56,801 --> 00:40:59,471
all that nice, even in my eyes.

1159
00:40:59,831 --> 00:41:02,340
They looked far from ordinary.

1160
00:41:02,341 --> 00:41:05,141
When I came back from work, my wife said,

1161
00:41:05,641 --> 00:41:08,181
"Honey. Our neighbor seems strange."

1162
00:41:08,911 --> 00:41:10,680
"Is that so?" But I was rarely at home...

1163
00:41:10,681 --> 00:41:12,111
- as I had to play baseball.
- Right.

1164
00:41:12,381 --> 00:41:14,851
If my neighbor seems suspicious,

1165
00:41:15,151 --> 00:41:16,280
- You get worried.
- it's concerning,

1166
00:41:16,281 --> 00:41:17,551
especially when I'm playing an away game.

1167
00:41:17,721 --> 00:41:20,861
Out of the blue, that house was on sale.

1168
00:41:21,991 --> 00:41:23,820
I was passing by when I saw the sign...

1169
00:41:23,821 --> 00:41:25,930
- that said the house was on sale.
- That's common in the US.

1170
00:41:25,931 --> 00:41:27,231
"Let's also buy that house."

1171
00:41:30,801 --> 00:41:32,170
That's like the game Blue Marble.

1172
00:41:32,171 --> 00:41:34,100
It's similar, although not exactly the same.

1173
00:41:34,101 --> 00:41:36,871
With my big body, it's uncomfortable to sit in one chair at the movies.

1174
00:41:37,201 --> 00:41:38,341
"What do I do? Okay."

1175
00:41:38,711 --> 00:41:39,940
"Let's also buy the seat next to mine."

1176
00:41:39,941 --> 00:41:41,611
- That's how you ended up buying it.
- Gosh.

1177
00:41:41,911 --> 00:41:44,450
- Isn't that the same vibe?
- If you don't like JTBC...

1178
00:41:44,451 --> 00:41:46,611
after the show, are you going to buy it?

1179
00:41:47,181 --> 00:41:48,481
But I love it.

1180
00:41:49,151 --> 00:41:50,280
(Adding JTBC into Choo's basket)

1181
00:41:50,281 --> 00:41:52,451
- Right?
- That was cute.

1182
00:41:52,551 --> 00:41:54,020
- After...
- He's funny.

1183
00:41:54,021 --> 00:41:56,161
the "major leaguer" on the Choo Choo Train log,

1184
00:41:56,221 --> 00:41:58,691
he wrote, "a generous donor."

1185
00:41:59,331 --> 00:42:02,101
The rumor that he's a generous donor in the baseball world...

1186
00:42:02,361 --> 00:42:03,731
is widely known.

1187
00:42:04,271 --> 00:42:05,371
But over the four years,

1188
00:42:06,331 --> 00:42:08,040
Shin Soo donated over three million dollars.

1189
00:42:08,041 --> 00:42:09,770
- That's amazing.
- Unbelievable.

1190
00:42:09,771 --> 00:42:11,841
He donated during the four years he was active in Korea, right?

1191
00:42:12,041 --> 00:42:15,211
He practically donated his whole annual income.

1192
00:42:15,341 --> 00:42:17,010
He donated the last season's annual income.

1193
00:42:17,011 --> 00:42:18,151
The whole thing?

1194
00:42:18,981 --> 00:42:22,050
I don't think giving away my annual income...

1195
00:42:22,051 --> 00:42:23,820
- was a donation.
- How come?

1196
00:42:23,821 --> 00:42:24,990
- What do you think it is?
- Then what?

1197
00:42:24,991 --> 00:42:26,521
When I first came to Korea,

1198
00:42:26,651 --> 00:42:31,091
the offer I received was a generous amount of 2.7 million dollars.

1199
00:42:31,461 --> 00:42:34,501
The original contract was only for a year.

1200
00:42:35,101 --> 00:42:38,130
But I had so much fun playing with the Korean players.

1201
00:42:38,131 --> 00:42:39,201
Right.

1202
00:42:39,301 --> 00:42:41,271
I talked a lot to others in the US, but...

1203
00:42:41,371 --> 00:42:42,701
- It's easier to communicate.
- Exactly.

1204
00:42:42,771 --> 00:42:45,470
- I can chat, joke around, - You can really open up.

1205
00:42:45,471 --> 00:42:46,971
and share personal things in Korean.

1206
00:42:47,271 --> 00:42:50,110
Younger players felt like actual younger brothers to me.

1207
00:42:50,111 --> 00:42:52,951
I wanted to help them...

1208
00:42:53,281 --> 00:42:57,081
play baseball in a better environment.

1209
00:42:57,591 --> 00:43:00,151
That kept me playing for another year, then two, and got me this far.

1210
00:43:00,351 --> 00:43:02,790
On YouTube, there was a video...

1211
00:43:02,791 --> 00:43:05,031
of your wife selling your car in secret.

1212
00:43:05,231 --> 00:43:06,630
- I know, right?
- To donate?

1213
00:43:06,631 --> 00:43:08,030
- It was no ordinary car.
- Exactly.

1214
00:43:08,031 --> 00:43:10,031
- The car was a Bentley. A real...
- Gosh.

1215
00:43:10,131 --> 00:43:12,670
That wasn't anything worth fighting over.

1216
00:43:12,671 --> 00:43:14,600
- It wasn't?
- It was for a great purpose.

1217
00:43:14,601 --> 00:43:16,070
Wouldn't that be a reason to get a divorce for us?

1218
00:43:16,071 --> 00:43:18,510
Was it a total surprise for you? Or did you have an idea about it?

1219
00:43:18,511 --> 00:43:22,041
My wife saw me off on the day...

1220
00:43:22,341 --> 00:43:23,711
I was leaving for the US.

1221
00:43:23,811 --> 00:43:26,311
But her seeing me off felt...

1222
00:43:27,081 --> 00:43:28,681
- Your hunch?
- a little off.

1223
00:43:29,051 --> 00:43:30,121
- Something was fishy.
- Yes.

1224
00:43:30,451 --> 00:43:32,620
My wife asked what she should do with my car.

1225
00:43:32,621 --> 00:43:33,750
I told her to keep...

1226
00:43:33,751 --> 00:43:35,020
the engine running.

1227
00:43:35,021 --> 00:43:36,820
Or else, the car would die.

1228
00:43:36,821 --> 00:43:38,461
My wife said she'd do that and asked...

1229
00:43:38,561 --> 00:43:39,961
if I wasn't going to sell it.

1230
00:43:40,161 --> 00:43:41,161
When I told her not now,

1231
00:43:41,162 --> 00:43:42,361
she said she would get a rough estimate.

1232
00:43:42,801 --> 00:43:44,170
- That was how much you knew.
- Yes.

1233
00:43:44,171 --> 00:43:45,431
(The day of Choo Shin Soo's departure)

1234
00:43:45,531 --> 00:43:47,201
(I'll be back soon.)

1235
00:43:47,801 --> 00:43:50,571
(I'll be away for one month.)

1236
00:43:50,771 --> 00:43:52,911
(Start the car every now and then.)

1237
00:43:53,141 --> 00:43:54,481
(A ghost?)

1238
00:43:54,611 --> 00:43:56,881
(Or the battery...)

1239
00:43:56,981 --> 00:43:57,981
(will die.)

1240
00:43:58,911 --> 00:44:00,080
(Choo Shin Soo's Bentley)

1241
00:44:00,081 --> 00:44:01,321
(Choo Shin Soo's beloved car)

1242
00:44:02,151 --> 00:44:04,991
(The final moment of the beloved car)

1243
00:44:05,751 --> 00:44:07,220
(Start the car, okay?)

1244
00:44:07,221 --> 00:44:08,221
(Okay.)

1245
00:44:08,222 --> 00:44:09,720
(I'll take good care of it.)

1246
00:44:09,721 --> 00:44:11,160
My wife was going to get an estimate.

1247
00:44:11,161 --> 00:44:14,061
I was in the US when a friend called me and asked,

1248
00:44:14,231 --> 00:44:15,561
"Did you sell your car?"

1249
00:44:16,501 --> 00:44:17,571
"No."

1250
00:44:17,771 --> 00:44:19,430
"My wife was only getting an estimate."

1251
00:44:19,431 --> 00:44:20,840
My friend burst out into laughter...

1252
00:44:20,841 --> 00:44:22,401
and told me to watch the YouTube video right away.

1253
00:44:23,571 --> 00:44:25,211
- (- Are you selling it for real?
- (Yes.)

1254
00:44:25,711 --> 00:44:27,171
(Won Mi is dead serious.)

1255
00:44:28,141 --> 00:44:29,881
She took a video and uploaded it?

1256
00:44:30,341 --> 00:44:31,410
(The car alone is...)

1257
00:44:31,411 --> 00:44:34,281
(The resale price of a Bentley is mid-to-high 40,000 dollars.)

1258
00:44:34,451 --> 00:44:35,881
(Mid-to-high 40,000 dollars?)

1259
00:44:36,521 --> 00:44:38,550
- Did you know by watching it?
- It's up for auction now.

1260
00:44:38,551 --> 00:44:40,421
- On the app marketplace?
- No.

1261
00:44:41,391 --> 00:44:44,990
Even though we were married, I was hardly ever home...

1262
00:44:44,991 --> 00:44:46,360
and had to travel quite often.

1263
00:44:46,361 --> 00:44:48,231
My wife raised our children alone.

1264
00:44:48,561 --> 00:44:50,461
As she raised three children alone,

1265
00:44:50,731 --> 00:44:53,130
- It must've been tough.
- we were like...

1266
00:44:53,131 --> 00:44:55,170
- a single-parent family.
- A single-parent family.

1267
00:44:55,171 --> 00:44:56,301
So...

1268
00:44:57,071 --> 00:44:59,540
We decided to donate the money...

1269
00:44:59,541 --> 00:45:01,611
to the organization we were always interested in.

1270
00:45:01,781 --> 00:45:03,640
With that, the money will be donated.

1271
00:45:03,641 --> 00:45:06,580
Let's now move on to "life of a B.N."

1272
00:45:06,581 --> 00:45:08,751
It must stand for baseball nerd.

1273
00:45:09,051 --> 00:45:10,751
- Gi Ru and Yun Hwa...
- Yes?

1274
00:45:11,191 --> 00:45:14,461
I've been waiting for this. It says "baseball stadium foodie."

1275
00:45:15,091 --> 00:45:17,861
What was your favorite food on your first visit to the stadium, Yun Hwa?

1276
00:45:17,991 --> 00:45:19,530
I went to the Munhak Baseball Stadium.

1277
00:45:19,531 --> 00:45:22,160
The food at the Munhak Baseball Stadium is like a buffet.

1278
00:45:22,161 --> 00:45:23,631
Each floor has some sort of food.

1279
00:45:23,731 --> 00:45:26,530
The lines are different depending on which way you go...

1280
00:45:26,531 --> 00:45:28,170
- from the entrance.
- Right.

1281
00:45:28,171 --> 00:45:31,441
- The food is delicious.
- Foods like mayonnaise shrimp...

1282
00:45:31,671 --> 00:45:33,810
are in every seat.

1283
00:45:33,811 --> 00:45:35,540
- Mayonnaise shrimp?
- Creamy mayonnaise shrimp.

1284
00:45:35,541 --> 00:45:36,740
- It's creamy mayonnaise shrimp.
- Sounds good.

1285
00:45:36,741 --> 00:45:38,810
When it's fall and people crave something spicy,

1286
00:45:38,811 --> 00:45:40,580
- they order mala shrimp.
- Yes.

1287
00:45:40,581 --> 00:45:43,080
Each table has mala shrimp.

1288
00:45:43,081 --> 00:45:44,921
There are three flavors of deep-fried braised chicken.

1289
00:45:45,121 --> 00:45:48,221
Honey mustard, salt, and...

1290
00:45:48,491 --> 00:45:49,961
- Have you not tried them?
- Wait.

1291
00:45:50,561 --> 00:45:53,230
- "Have you not tried them?"
- Why haven't you tried them?

1292
00:45:53,231 --> 00:45:55,731
I thought you were a Munhak Baseball Stadium staff member.

1293
00:45:56,561 --> 00:46:00,201
Listen. I mentioned this almost every day.

1294
00:46:00,531 --> 00:46:03,041
I wish pro basketball were like that.

1295
00:46:03,171 --> 00:46:06,540
At first, people tag along with their friends...

1296
00:46:06,541 --> 00:46:09,240
- without knowing the rules.
- Exactly.

1297
00:46:09,241 --> 00:46:10,410
- Yes.
- Then, they become fans themselves.

1298
00:46:10,411 --> 00:46:11,811
- I became a fan.
- And when they do,

1299
00:46:11,951 --> 00:46:14,051
- there could be various reasons.
- Of course.

1300
00:46:14,351 --> 00:46:15,981
For example, like Yun Hwa,

1301
00:46:16,181 --> 00:46:19,291
she fell in love with the food first,

1302
00:46:19,651 --> 00:46:21,690
and then became a fan as she kept eating.

1303
00:46:21,691 --> 00:46:22,720
I didn't become a fan while eating.

1304
00:46:22,721 --> 00:46:23,920
- All right.
- No, Jang Hoon.

1305
00:46:23,921 --> 00:46:26,331
Either way, those well-equipped facilities...

1306
00:46:26,531 --> 00:46:29,930
helped make pro baseball popular.

1307
00:46:29,931 --> 00:46:31,430
I wish basketball also gained popularity.

1308
00:46:31,431 --> 00:46:34,340
I know. That's so cool. The fritter place in front of...

1309
00:46:34,341 --> 00:46:36,100
the KCC basketball court is delicious.

1310
00:46:36,101 --> 00:46:37,201
Is that the only popular thing?

1311
00:46:37,301 --> 00:46:38,810
How do you know something even I don't?

1312
00:46:38,811 --> 00:46:40,341
The fried bread is amazing.

1313
00:46:40,871 --> 00:46:42,310
So you didn't know.

1314
00:46:42,311 --> 00:46:44,450
Do you two often go to watch the game in person?

1315
00:46:44,451 --> 00:46:45,610
- What's the plan?
- Yes, we did.

1316
00:46:45,611 --> 00:46:46,710
We often did.

1317
00:46:46,711 --> 00:46:49,880
People think we go to the games just to make videos.

1318
00:46:49,881 --> 00:46:53,250
But that's not true. We love baseball.

1319
00:46:53,251 --> 00:46:55,160
- It's too hot to go in the summer.
- Right.

1320
00:46:55,161 --> 00:46:56,290
The barbecue place.

1321
00:46:56,291 --> 00:46:57,790
There are over a dozen...

1322
00:46:57,791 --> 00:46:59,330
- barbecue zones.
- It must be bothersome.

1323
00:46:59,331 --> 00:47:01,300
The zone is for fans to dine in, right?

1324
00:47:01,301 --> 00:47:03,300
Booking that zone isn't easy at all.

1325
00:47:03,301 --> 00:47:04,770
- Do you have to book it?
- It's competitive.

1326
00:47:04,771 --> 00:47:06,671
The zones are fully booked on the weekends.

1327
00:47:06,801 --> 00:47:08,440
Eating at the barbecue zone...

1328
00:47:08,441 --> 00:47:10,741
Watching baseball is great in itself.

1329
00:47:10,841 --> 00:47:13,710
But I just love enjoying the food with close friends,

1330
00:47:13,711 --> 00:47:16,110
like a get-together in a garden,

1331
00:47:16,111 --> 00:47:17,380
while watching the game.

1332
00:47:17,381 --> 00:47:19,010
From the 1st to the 9th inning,

1333
00:47:19,011 --> 00:47:20,580
you had different types of meat, didn't you?

1334
00:47:20,581 --> 00:47:22,151
Yes. We had 11 different types of meat.

1335
00:47:22,851 --> 00:47:25,050
You could have more if the game goes overtime.

1336
00:47:25,051 --> 00:47:26,350
- Yes.
- You have to return the grill...

1337
00:47:26,351 --> 00:47:27,690
by the eighth inning.

1338
00:47:27,691 --> 00:47:30,261
But you don't have to if you bring your own.

1339
00:47:30,561 --> 00:47:32,030
So... What was it again?

1340
00:47:32,031 --> 00:47:34,500
- Can you take your own grill?
- I take my own grill.

1341
00:47:34,501 --> 00:47:36,430
I just have to finish eating...

1342
00:47:36,431 --> 00:47:38,330
before the audience leaves after the ninth inning.

1343
00:47:38,331 --> 00:47:40,871
I remember buying 9 or 11 types of meat.

1344
00:47:41,041 --> 00:47:42,900
Can the outfielders on the field...

1345
00:47:42,901 --> 00:47:44,510
- smell the meat?
- Can you smell it?

1346
00:47:44,511 --> 00:47:47,471
In my first 2 years, 2021 and 2022,

1347
00:47:47,781 --> 00:47:49,941
I played defense as a right fielder.

1348
00:47:50,341 --> 00:47:54,051
When I take the field, I can already smell...

1349
00:47:54,181 --> 00:47:55,580
the kimchi grilled in pork belly fat.

1350
00:47:55,581 --> 00:47:56,781
Can you smell the kimchi?

1351
00:47:57,921 --> 00:47:59,920
(Who is it?)

1352
00:47:59,921 --> 00:48:03,021
(Who grilled pork belly and kimchi?)

1353
00:48:03,261 --> 00:48:06,361
I don't eat anything before a game.

1354
00:48:06,661 --> 00:48:07,901
- Most don't.
- It's because...

1355
00:48:08,131 --> 00:48:10,401
as I got older, my digestive system got weaker.

1356
00:48:10,761 --> 00:48:12,201
That's why I don't eat anything.

1357
00:48:12,431 --> 00:48:14,100
But that smell...

1358
00:48:14,101 --> 00:48:15,740
- I didn't know you could smell it.
- is hard to put up with.

1359
00:48:15,741 --> 00:48:18,241
I must've grilled a whole head of kimchi back then.

1360
00:48:18,811 --> 00:48:21,011
I must've grilled a whole head of kimchi back then.

1361
00:48:21,981 --> 00:48:23,341
It must have been that day.

1362
00:48:23,781 --> 00:48:27,010
I heard you and Yun Hwa weren't meeting up often these days.

1363
00:48:27,011 --> 00:48:28,220
- Yun Hwa is avoiding me.
- Why?

1364
00:48:28,221 --> 00:48:29,520
- You two are besties.
- Yes.

1365
00:48:29,521 --> 00:48:31,620
- She's on a diet.
- I'm on a diet these days.

1366
00:48:31,621 --> 00:48:32,850
Yes.

1367
00:48:32,851 --> 00:48:34,790
Whenever I go to a baseball game,

1368
00:48:34,791 --> 00:48:36,590
- I gain weight.
- Of course.

1369
00:48:36,591 --> 00:48:39,130
But she didn't gain weight just because of the baseball games.

1370
00:48:39,131 --> 00:48:41,230
She has been going to those games for a year or two now.

1371
00:48:41,231 --> 00:48:42,860
She was still fat before then.

1372
00:48:42,861 --> 00:48:45,730
I don't know why she would suddenly say that.

1373
00:48:45,731 --> 00:48:48,040
Yun Hwa, you met a doppelganger, right?

1374
00:48:48,041 --> 00:48:49,100
- A doppelganger?
- Yes.

1375
00:48:49,101 --> 00:48:50,571
- Yes, recently.
- She did.

1376
00:48:50,701 --> 00:48:52,240
- He looked so much like me...
- I love him.

1377
00:48:52,241 --> 00:48:53,310
- that even I was surprised.
- Yes.

1378
00:48:53,311 --> 00:48:55,241
- It's ZO ZAZZ.
- That's right.

1379
00:48:56,041 --> 00:48:59,051
- I saw him on your Instagram.
- The two of them...

1380
00:49:00,251 --> 00:49:01,420
This is Yun Hwa, right?

1381
00:49:01,421 --> 00:49:02,921
- No, that's ZO ZAZZ.
- No.

1382
00:49:04,351 --> 00:49:05,750
- Really?
- This is me.

1383
00:49:05,751 --> 00:49:06,791
What?

1384
00:49:07,321 --> 00:49:08,560
(Why can't you tell who is who?)

1385
00:49:08,561 --> 00:49:10,421
- That's so funny.
- This is ZO ZAZZ.

1386
00:49:10,721 --> 00:49:12,130
- I really can't tell.
- That's so funny.

1387
00:49:12,131 --> 00:49:13,890
How did you get that shot?

1388
00:49:13,891 --> 00:49:15,030
You look so much alike.

1389
00:49:15,031 --> 00:49:16,601
- Gosh.
- This is me.

1390
00:49:17,031 --> 00:49:19,370
How did you get to shoot this? That was so cool.

1391
00:49:19,371 --> 00:49:22,240
One day, people kept mentioning...

1392
00:49:22,241 --> 00:49:24,040
"ZO ZAZZ..."

1393
00:49:24,041 --> 00:49:25,870
- on my Instagram and YouTube.
- "ZO ZAZZ."

1394
00:49:25,871 --> 00:49:27,811
"You sing so well."

1395
00:49:27,881 --> 00:49:29,640
- So I wondered what that was about.
- The people mentioned him?

1396
00:49:29,641 --> 00:49:31,381
I didn't know who he was, but when I saw him,

1397
00:49:31,551 --> 00:49:33,081
he really did look like me.

1398
00:49:33,211 --> 00:49:35,650
We are the certain type that are...

1399
00:49:35,651 --> 00:49:38,021
We are a bit round-looking.

1400
00:49:38,251 --> 00:49:39,420
Round-looking.

1401
00:49:39,421 --> 00:49:42,020
- Those that look a bit round.
- Yes.

1402
00:49:42,021 --> 00:49:44,761
- The video was a sudden hit.
- That's right.

1403
00:49:45,161 --> 00:49:49,631
(HONG ZAZZ sings with a bottle of soy sauce at home.)

1404
00:49:49,861 --> 00:49:52,301
(Singing)

1405
00:49:52,801 --> 00:49:54,100
(I love ZO ZAZZ's songs, so I was watching Shorts,)

1406
00:49:54,101 --> 00:49:55,301
(and I didn't notice anything wrong. I thought it was really him.)

1407
00:49:55,501 --> 00:49:57,740
I told him that we should meet up.

1408
00:49:57,741 --> 00:49:59,040
- "Let's meet up."
- You contacted him first?

1409
00:49:59,041 --> 00:50:01,811
Yes, so we sat back to back and shot that.

1410
00:50:01,981 --> 00:50:03,640
- They look so much alike.
- Did you need makeup for that?

1411
00:50:03,641 --> 00:50:06,381
No, I didn't do anything. I just put on a jacket.

1412
00:50:06,551 --> 00:50:07,950
You didn't need any makeup?

1413
00:50:07,951 --> 00:50:10,281
- No, I just drew a mustache.
- You didn't need any makeup?

1414
00:50:10,521 --> 00:50:11,620
- It's just me.
- That's just her.

1415
00:50:11,621 --> 00:50:13,890
- He promised to buy you meat?
- He treated me, recently.

1416
00:50:13,891 --> 00:50:14,891
- Really?
- Already?

1417
00:50:14,892 --> 00:50:16,620
I think I can just say that...

1418
00:50:16,621 --> 00:50:19,691
his wallet broke apart, trying to treat me with meat.

1419
00:50:21,401 --> 00:50:23,730
He told me to eat as much as I want.

1420
00:50:23,731 --> 00:50:25,201
So I did.

1421
00:50:25,271 --> 00:50:28,071
Last is Hyun Soo.

1422
00:50:28,341 --> 00:50:29,900
What he wrote was...

1423
00:50:29,901 --> 00:50:31,671
"First pitch in full gear."

1424
00:50:31,941 --> 00:50:33,540
What kind of full hear would you need for that?

1425
00:50:33,541 --> 00:50:35,980
- He did the first pitch.
- For women, it could be...

1426
00:50:35,981 --> 00:50:37,740
It must mean that he even wore the uniform pants.

1427
00:50:37,741 --> 00:50:39,080
You're right. What Jang Hoon said is right.

1428
00:50:39,081 --> 00:50:41,251
People don't usually wear all that.

1429
00:50:41,321 --> 00:50:42,750
- I...
- Usually, they only wear the top.

1430
00:50:42,751 --> 00:50:45,120
That's right. They usually wear the top with jeans.

1431
00:50:45,121 --> 00:50:47,520
I was watching TV one day,

1432
00:50:47,521 --> 00:50:51,121
and I saw Zo In Sung, who is a famous Hanwha fan.

1433
00:50:51,391 --> 00:50:53,430
He was wearing the full uniform for the first pitch,

1434
00:50:53,431 --> 00:50:55,031
and he looked so amazing.

1435
00:50:55,231 --> 00:50:56,931
He looked like a true fan.

1436
00:50:57,001 --> 00:51:00,731
So, I planned to wear it all if I got the chance one day.

1437
00:51:00,831 --> 00:51:03,940
That's why I got all geared up, even with the cleats,

1438
00:51:03,941 --> 00:51:05,370
- for the first pitch.
- Even the cleats?

1439
00:51:05,371 --> 00:51:07,370
- I wanted to wear it all, - Did you do a good job?

1440
00:51:07,371 --> 00:51:09,380
- so I did.
- And what about the throw?

1441
00:51:09,381 --> 00:51:11,080
I was so nervous.

1442
00:51:11,081 --> 00:51:12,650
- Yes, it's so intimidating.
- I was always...

1443
00:51:12,651 --> 00:51:15,651
only watching from the bleachers, but I was standing on the mound,

1444
00:51:15,951 --> 00:51:18,051
and had all the attention from the audience.

1445
00:51:18,451 --> 00:51:21,150
My shoulders suddenly became tense,

1446
00:51:21,151 --> 00:51:22,720
- and I missed the release point.
- Oh, no.

1447
00:51:22,721 --> 00:51:24,221
- So I let go with my arm out.
- Goodness.

1448
00:51:24,491 --> 00:51:26,560
And the ball went directly to the opponent's knees.

1449
00:51:26,561 --> 00:51:27,831
- Goodness. And then?
- What?

1450
00:51:28,461 --> 00:51:32,171
(The top fan is nervous with his full gear.)

1451
00:51:34,701 --> 00:51:38,141
(He almost hit the opponent's knees.)

1452
00:51:38,511 --> 00:51:41,210
- That really is legendary.
- I was hated on like never before.

1453
00:51:41,211 --> 00:51:42,611
- From the opponent team's fans.
- Yes.

